title: For Sale:  Highly improved Remington 700 in 308 Win
postcontent:
I have a remington 700 that I built a number of years ago but haven't shot in a while. The gun shot incredibly well, I just don't get it out much anymore because I enjoy handgun shooting more now.

Let me give you a quick rundown of the gun. I purchased the gun for about $700 as a new Remington 700 BDL Varmint model with a 26" bull barrel in 308 Winchester. It holds 4 rounds in its internal box magazine. I have done a lot of things to improve it though, here's a quick list:

Fire Lapped the barrel using David Tubb's fire lapping bullets. Did this early on in the guns life using a very careful procedure as outlined with the bullets. It really did help and made cleaning it so much easier.

Trigger job- It has the X-mark pro trigger on it, I adjusted it down to somewhere in the neighboorhood of 2 lbs (I don't have a scale to measure it, but it breaks like glass). 

Replaced the plastic stock- The gun came with an injection molded plastic stock. I got rid of that cheap plastic thing as quick as possibe. I opted for the Hogue overmolded stock with a full aluminum bedding block that I bedded the action into using a Devcon steel putty that is resistant to chemicals. The barrel is completely free floated in it. The stock was about $190, plus the time and parts that are involved in bedding the action and floating the barrel (typical gunsmith charges $100-$200 plus parts). Also on the stock I installed a monte carlo cheek riser to better align my eye with the scope. It is the same rubber material as the Hogue stock, so it fits in nicely.

Replaced the firing pin- I installed a firing pin assembly with a slightly higher power spring. The firing pin assembly ran about $70.

Installed a Leupold Mark 4 scope rail with a 15 moa slope on it. The scope rail runs about $125. It will be included with the gun and will take any picatinny type scope rings. No scope is included with the gun.

That pretty well sums up my list of mods. Here's the bottom line, this gun (at least last time I shot it which was several years ago) shot like an absolute dream. I've got one of the last targets I shot with it in hand and will try to post a picture of it on here. I built it as a precision rifle because at the time I was trying to get into F-Class shooting. I want to be completely open and honest though so here is something not so great about it. The stock has a few scuff marks on it. 

The gun shot very well back when I was shooting it and I have no doubt it will again, I just don't have a use for it any longer. I'm asking $1000 for this gun with all of it's improvements. I do require a bill of sale on any gun that I sell even though it is not required by law, it is so I can keep track of what I have sold.  If you are unwilling to fill one out then please do not reply.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Winchester M1 (.30 cal) Carbine Manufactured Feb-Nov. 1944/Excellent Condition & All Oirginal!
postcontent:
I have a Winchester M1 Carbine for sale. Made between Feb '44 and Nov '44. This rifle has a lot of history and is in really good condition. the rifle comes with 1 30 round mag. and 1 15 round mag. 

I am asking $600 OBO and will accept only cash. I will also only meet local in the Everett or a surrounding city close by. I am open to partial or full trades as long as it totals the asking price. I may be willing to toss in a little cash myself for the right trade deal.

It has a Winchester receiver, barrel and stock with 2 hole upper hand guard and type 2 rear sight. The stock variation is oval sling cut with low wood that exposes slide. It has the W.R.A/G.H.D. with the crossed cannons stamp inspection marks from Winchester Repeating Arms and the G.H.D. were the initials of the inspector in charge of that district. It was marked by a "U" for Underwood which means it had some parts replaced for better functionality. My M1 had the barrel band, slide, magazine catch, safety and sight all changed to improve function as mentioned above. 

I copy and pasted my source for this as well as the paragraph that discusses it. 


http://www.bavarianm1carbines.com/partsbparts.html

"The U.S. Caliber .30 Carbines consisted of 56-81 parts, depending on the model and time of manufacture.
U.S. Ordnance redesigned a number of parts over the course of production and after WWII, several parts more than once. Most of these changes were to improve reliability and/or function, manufacture time, and/or cost. None of the changes were so critical as to merit a massive recall. A few of these changes were important enough to merit replacing the earlier part with the later variant when the carbine could be inspected by U.S. Ordnance personnel. For most carbines this wouldn't happen until after the end of the war.
Two of the unique things about the U.S. GI M1 Carbines are almost all of the parts are backwards and forwards compatible regardless of whatever change was made, and, all of the parts are interchangeable from one carbine to another without requiring individual fitting."

Designed by Pat Crawford, the Triumph NECK is a no-nonsense emergency compact knife designed to always be on hand. Its 1/8" thick blade of 3Cr13 stainless steel. Users just tie the cord through the eyelets of the Triumph NECK sheath and slip the harness over their shoulders for comfort and concealability under uniforms, tactical vests or even T-shirts. Drawing from the harness is lightning quick with either a cross draw to the forward grip, or a same-side draw to a reverse grip.
